There are many allusione in this satire to persons and events, but none sufficiently definite to fix the date of composition. Evidently it was written aster Sat. 4 and therefore alter 2, 7, and 8,·somewhere between 38 nc. and 35. The large circle of friends whose names are mentioned in the closing lines would indicate a late date, and the general tone is that oi an epilogue to the whole collection, as the first satire is an introduction to the whole. This interpretation also har- monizes with the last line oi the satire (see notes).

‘It is quite true thatI said that Lucilius was a rough verse writer. His power as a satirist l acknowledge, hut that alone does not makea poet. Many other qualities are necessary to a poetic style, brevity, variety, wit, such polished wit as is found in the Old Comedy, of which, indeed, some ol my critioe seem never to have heard. The mingling of Greek with Latin in Lucilius is not a merit, but a defect, no serious Roman writer mixes the two languages or writes in Greek at all.

‘The grand style l leave to others to attempt, successfully or not. My aim is less ambitlous. The fields of comedy and tragedy, of epic and bucolic poetry, are well occupied and I have turned to satire, not, however, to be the rival ol Lucilius or to lessen his glory. But it is true that 1 have mentioned his defects, as he had noticed the defects of Ennius and Accius. The copiousness ol Lucilius and his lack of

finish are real defects, which, it he were writing nov, he would himself ’

perceive and correct.
